1. Add USB Input Protection

    Recommend an ESD protection diode array on the USB-C VBUS and CC lines to improve robustness against electrostatic discharge.
    Consider a resettable polyfuse on VBUS to protect the board from accidental shorts or excessive input current.

2. Improve ADC Measurement Stability

    Add a small capacitor (typically 100 nF) across the lower resistor of the battery voltage divider to form a low-pass filter. This reduces ADC noise and provides more stable battery readings.

3. Increase Local Decoupling on the Motor Driver

    The DRV8837 should have a dedicated 100 nF ceramic capacitor placed immediately adjacent to the VM supply pin in addition to the existing bulk capacitor to suppress switching transients.

4. Review Boost Converter Feedback Network

    Verify that the resistor divider values actually produce the intended 6 V output and confirm they comply with the regulator's recommended operating range.

5. Improve LDO Output Stability

    While the MCP1700 will operate with the current capacitors, increasing the output capacitance (e.g., to 4.7 µF) provides better transient response during MCU and LED load changes.

6. Optimize Speaker Driver

    In addition to adding the series resistor, replace the through-hole 2N2222 with an SOT-23 transistor (MMBT2222A or BC817) to match the SMT assembly process.

7. Replace Through-Hole Components

    Replace the 1N4148 DO-35 diode with an SMD equivalent (1N4148WS/BAS16) to maintain a fully SMT assembly.

8. Thermal Design Considerations

    Verify that the BQ24040 exposed pad and the DRV8837 thermal pad are connected to a solid ground plane with sufficient thermal vias for heat dissipation.

9. components layout on pcb
    re layout all the componets and mounting holes on the pcb to make sure all are aligned.

10. Decoupling Placement

 Ensure every IC's bypass capacitor is physically located as close as possible to its supply pins. This cannot be confirmed from the schematic but should be verified during layout review.

11. Battery Protection Path Verification

 Confirm the DW01A and dual MOSFET orientation matches the recommended application circuit so that over-charge, over-discharge, and over-current protection operate correctly.

12. PWM/Motor Control Readiness

 Verify the chosen STM32 timer channels support true hardware PWM on the selected DRV8837 input pins to meet the requirement for smooth, jitter-free motor control.


